835","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/ozone-151005201546-lva1-app6892-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Ozone is a molecule composed of three oxygen atoms that absorbs ultraviolet radiation. It is found in both the stratosphere, where it forms an important protective ozone layer, and at ground level as a component of smog. The document discusses the composition and properties of ozone, how the stratospheric ozone layer can be depleted by man-made chemicals like CFCs, and the significance of monitoring ozone levels globally.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/ozone-layer-53566835/53566835","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":704},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Biosafety level 3","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":6,"score":0,"slideshowId":"48085700","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"biosafety-level-3-48085700","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/biosafetylevel3-150513072346-lva1-app6891-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Biosafety Level 3 is for work with indigenous or exotic agents that may cause serious disease through inhalation. Specific training is required for personnel, and all procedures with infectious materials must be done in a biosafety cabinet or other containment device. A BSL-3 laboratory has special engineering controls and stringent safety practices, equipment, and facility requirements to contain the infectious agents and protect personnel. These include restricted access, personal protective equipment, specific facility design features, and procedures for containment, decontamination, and medical management following any exposures.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/biosafety-level-3-48085700/48085700","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":758},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"biosafety levels ","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":20,"score":0,"slideshowId":"53777890","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"biosafety-levels-53777890","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/principleofbiosafty-151010200414-lva1-app6892-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"The document discusses containment methods for safely handling biohazardous agents in laboratories. Primary containment involves good microbiological techniques and safety equipment like biological safety cabinets to protect personnel and the immediate lab environment. Secondary containment uses facility design and practices to protect the external environment. Containment aims to reduce exposure risks for lab workers and prevent agents from escaping outside. The document then describes different biosafety levels based on the hazard level of the agents and appropriate safety measures for each level.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/biosafety-levels-53777890/53777890","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":605},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Preparing smears for staining","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":5,"score":0,"slideshowId":"56527670","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"preparing-smears-for-staining","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/preparingsmearsforstaining-151229165924-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"This document discusses procedures for preparing and staining microbial smears and slides. It describes how microbes are fixed to slides through air drying or heat, and then stained using simple, differential or special staining techniques. Key points covered include how gram staining classifies bacteria as either gram-positive or gram-negative based on cell wall structure and staining properties, and how acid-fast staining identifies mycobacteria by their lipid-rich cell walls. Negative staining can reveal capsules around cells.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/preparing-smears-for-staining/56527670","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":4595},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"types of Cancer ","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":5,"score":0,"slideshowId":"59051740","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"types-of-cancer-59051740","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/cancerexplained-160304035544-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Cancer is a disease caused by changes in cells that lead to uncontrolled growth and the formation of tumors. If left untreated, tumors can grow and spread through the body. There are many known causes of cancer including carcinogens, genetics, age, lifestyle factors like smoking, diet, and infections. Early detection and prevention efforts like vaccination programs and screening can help reduce cancer rates globally. However, cancer remains a major public health challenge worldwide with rates expected to continue rising due to factors such as aging populations and increases in risk factors. Unless urgent action is taken, millions more people will die prematurely from cancer each year.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/types-of-cancer-59051740/59051740","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":431},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Cancer explained","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":5,"score":0,"slideshowId":"59051705","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"cancer-explained-59051705","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/cancerexplained-160304035444-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Cancer is a disease caused by changes in cells that lead to uncontrolled growth and the formation of tumors. If left untreated, tumors can grow and spread through the body via the bloodstream and lymphatic system. There are over 200 known types of cancer that can be classified as carcinomas, sarcomas, lymphomas, or leukemias depending on the cells affected. Cancers are caused by a combination of genetic and environmental factors like carcinogens, age, genetics, immune system, diet, tobacco, radiation, infections, and other lifestyle and workplace factors. Common signs of cancer include lumps, changes in bowel or bladder habits, unusual bleeding, unexplained weight loss, and fatigue. The global burden of cancer is","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/cancer-explained-59051705/59051705","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":138},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Shigella.....","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":6,"score":0,"slideshowId":"54218035","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"shigella-54218035","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/shigella-151021134923-lva1-app6892-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Shigella is a genus of bacteria that causes the infectious disease shigellosis. The bacteria spread easily through contaminated food or surfaces and cause symptoms like diarrhea, abdominal cramps, and fever. Young children are most at risk. Treatment focuses on rehydration, though antibiotics may be needed for severe cases. Preventing the spread involves thorough handwashing, especially after using the bathroom or changing diapers.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/shigella-54218035/54218035","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":271},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Deforestation and causes of deforestion","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":5,"score":0,"slideshowId":"53519860","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"deforestation-and-causes-of-deforestion","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/deforestation-151004181451-lva1-app6891-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"The document discusses the causes and effects of deforestation. It identifies the main causes as timber production, cut and blaze farming, deforestation for grazing land, and using forests for firewood. Deforestation negatively impacts the environment, atmosphere, hydrology, soil, biodiversity, and human economies. Reforestation efforts include reducing emissions, sustainable farming practices, monitoring deforestation, and increasing protected areas. Overall, forests are important for ecological balance by providing habitat, producing oxygen, preventing land degradation, and being a source of timber.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/deforestation-and-causes-of-deforestion/53519860","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":1026},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Musculoskeletal System","extension":"doc","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":12,"score":0,"slideshowId":"48199310","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"physiology-notes1","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/physiologynotes1-150515165940-lva1-app6891-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"The musculoskeletal system consists of bones, joints, and muscles that work together to enable movement and protect internal organs. The skeleton provides structure and support, while joints allow bones to articulate and muscles to contract, producing movement. There are over 200 bones in the human body that form the framework for this system. Joints are where two or more bones connect, and can be immovable or freely movable. Muscles make up 40-50% of body weight and attach to bones via tendons, allowing motions like flexion, extension, and rotation when contracted. Landmarks, range of motion, and strength are assessed during a physical exam of this complex anatomical system.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/physiology-notes1/48199310","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":351},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Oxidative stress","extension":"pptx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":20,"score":0,"slideshowId":"43048885","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"oxidative-stress-43048885","type":"presentation","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/oxidativestress-141228075310-conversion-gate01-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Oxidative stress occurs when there is an excessive level of reactive oxygen species that overwhelm the body's antioxidant defenses. This can damage lipids, proteins, DNA and lead to diseases like atherosclerosis, heart disease, arthritis, obesity, and cancer. The body has antioxidant enzymes like superoxide dismutase and catalase, as well as antioxidant vitamins and minerals that help counteract oxidative stress. However, when oxidative stress is prolonged or severe, it can contribute to disease development and progression.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/oxidative-stress-43048885/43048885","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":1557},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Campylobacter","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":7,"score":0,"slideshowId":"54218215","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"campylobacter-54218215","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/campylobacter-151021135326-lva1-app6892-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Campylobacter is the leading cause of bacterial diarrhea in humans. It is commonly transmitted through contaminated or undercooked poultry, raw milk, or untreated water. Symptoms usually appear within 2 to 10 days and include diarrhea, fever, nausea, and abdominal pain. While most cases resolve on their own within a week, complications can occasionally occur such as Guillain-Barré syndrome. Proper food handling and cooking can help prevent Campylobacter infections.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/campylobacter-54218215/54218215","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":1367},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Rabies virus","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":5,"score":0,"slideshowId":"54650895","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"rabies-virus-54650895","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/rabiesvirus-151102162332-lva1-app6891-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"The rabies virus causes rabies in humans and animals through transmission via saliva. It is a neurotropic virus that attacks the central nervous system. The virus has a bullet-like shape and encodes 5 genes in its RNA genome. It enters host cells through endocytosis mediated by the glycoprotein and then hijacks the host cell machinery to replicate. The virus spreads from the site of infection along neural pathways to the brain and then to salivary glands. A post-exposure vaccine is effective but must be administered promptly along with immunoglobulin to prevent fatal rabies.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/rabies-virus-54650895/54650895","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":620},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"TYPES OF NUCLEIC ACIDS","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":10,"score":0,"slideshowId":"52283205","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"types-of-nucleic-acids","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/nucleicacids-150901080125-lva1-app6891-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Nucleic acids like DNA and RNA are long biopolymers composed of nucleotides. DNA stores genetic information in cells and is made up of deoxyribonucleotides arranged in a double helix structure. RNA is involved in protein synthesis and comes in several types including mRNA, tRNA, and rRNA. Nucleic acids have a primary structure defined by their linear sequence of nucleotides joined by phosphodiester bonds, and a secondary structure involving base pairing of nucleotides that gives them their characteristic helical shape.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/types-of-nucleic-acids/52283205","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":21702},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Malnutrition","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":5,"score":0,"slideshowId":"61577235","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"malnutrition-61577235","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/1-160502122753-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Malnutrition refers to deficiencies or excesses of nutrients that can harm health. There are two main types: undernutrition, meaning not enough calories and nutrients, and overnutrition, meaning too many calories. Undernutrition is widespread globally and a leading cause of death, while overnutrition can increase disease risks. Specific deficiencies can also cause diseases, with micronutrient deficiencies alone affecting over 2 billion people worldwide.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/malnutrition-61577235/61577235","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":2818},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Translation , Transcription and Transduction","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":9,"score":0,"slideshowId":"52037045","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"translation-transcription-and-transduction","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/translation-150825080739-lva1-app6892-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Translation is the process by which messenger RNA (mRNA) is used to produce proteins. It occurs in three main steps: initiation, elongation, and termination. During initiation, the ribosome assembles on the mRNA. In elongation, transfer RNAs (tRNAs) bring amino acids to the ribosome according to the mRNA codons, linking the amino acids into a polypeptide chain. In termination, a stop codon signals the ribosome to release the full protein. Translation allows genes encoded in DNA to be expressed as functional proteins through reading of mRNA templates.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/translation-transcription-and-transduction/52037045","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":11767},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Bacillus subtilis","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":6,"score":0,"slideshowId":"54114295","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"bacillus-subtilis-54114295","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/bacillussubtilis-151019121941-lva1-app6892-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Bacillus subtilis is a rod-shaped, Gram-positive bacterium commonly found in soil. It forms endospores that allow it to survive harsh environmental conditions. While traditionally considered an aerobe, recent studies have shown it can also grow anaerobically using various electron acceptors. B. subtilis is a model organism used to study processes like chromosome replication, cellular differentiation, and sporulation. It is also used industrially to produce secreted enzymes on a large scale.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/bacillus-subtilis-54114295/54114295","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":7077},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Citrobacter","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":7,"score":0,"slideshowId":"54114710","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"citrobacter-54114710","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/citrobacter-151019122917-lva1-app6891-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Citrobacter is a genus of Gram-negative bacteria that is commonly found in soil, water, and the intestinal tract of humans and animals. While usually harmless, some Citrobacter species can cause opportunistic infections, especially in immunocompromised patients. Citrobacter freundii is one of the most clinically significant species, known to cause infections of the urinary tract, respiratory tract, blood, and central nervous system. It has developed resistance to many antibiotics. Citrobacter infections in neonates can be serious, with meningitis being particularly dangerous. Diagnosis involves blood and CSF cultures, while treatment requires a combination of antibiotics and sometimes surgery.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/citrobacter-54114710/54114710","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":6934},{"algorithmId":"21","displayTitle":"Different Types of Vaccine","extension":"docx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":9,"score":0,"slideshowId":"48085415","sourceName":"li_interact","strippedTitle":"different-types-of-vaccine","type":"document","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/vaccine1-150513071505-lva1-app6891-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"The document discusses different types of vaccines, including live attenuated vaccines, inactivated vaccines, subunit vaccines, recombinant viral protein vaccines, synthetic peptide vaccines, anti-idiotype antibodies vaccines, and DNA vaccines. It provides details on how each type of vaccine is produced and advantages and disadvantages of each approach. Key points covered include methods used to attenuate viruses for live vaccines, challenges with developing inactivated vaccines, use of recombinant DNA technology to produce subunit and viral protein vaccines, and potential of DNA vaccines which directly inject DNA coding for antigens.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/different-types-of-vaccine/48085415","userLogin":"amjadkhanafridi4all","userName":"Amjad Khan Afridi (Microbiologist)","viewCount":11177}],"similarTo":[{"algorithmId":"11","displayTitle":"Kidney stone","extension":"ppt","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":10,"score":0.8328,"slideshowId":"8636218","sourceName":"cm_text_v2","strippedTitle":"kidney-stone","type":"presentation","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/kidneystone-110719100704-phpapp01-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Kidney stones form when crystals separate from urine and stick together inside the kidney or urinary tract. They can cause severe pain and blood in the urine. Risk factors include dehydration, family history, and medical conditions. Symptoms include intense pain in the back or side and blood in the urine. Diagnosis is usually done with a CT scan. Small stones often pass on their own but larger ones may require lithotripsy or surgery to break up the stones. Drinking plenty of water can help prevent kidney stones from forming.","tags":[],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/kidney-stone/8636218","userLogin":"kashifanwer","userName":"kashif Anwer","viewCou