":41},{"algorithmId":"4","displayTitle":"Malposition_Malpresentation.pdf preeti kulshrestha","extension":"pdf","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":54,"score":0,"slideshowId":"288013788","sourceName":"LATEST","strippedTitle":"malposition_malpresentation-pdf-preeti-kulshrestha","type":"presentation","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/malpositionmalpresentation-260611140222-efd7ff22-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"This document discusses fetal positioning and presentations during labor and delivery. It begins by defining non-vertex presentations including breech, face, brow, transverse, and compound. It then discusses the causes of non-vertex presentations and describes the different positions including occiput posterior. The document provides details on assessing various positions through abdominal and vaginal exams. It concludes by outlining the management of different non-vertex positions, including allowing natural rotation, augmentation of labor, operative vaginal delivery, or caesarean section if needed.","tags":["all nursing and medical stu.","all nursing students","presentations"],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/malposition_malpresentation-pdf-preeti-kulshrestha/288013788","userLogin":"PreetiKulshreshtha3","userName":"Preeti Kulshreshtha","viewCount":47},{"algorithmId":"4","displayTitle":"Cognitive Biases in Clinical Diagnosis How AI Acts as an External Calibrator ...","extension":"pptx","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":16,"score":0,"slideshowId":"287958396","sourceName":"LATEST","strippedTitle":"cognitive-biases-in-clinical-diagnosis-how-ai-acts-as-an-external-calibrator-in-managed-chaos-eduar-pptx","type":"presentation","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/cognitivebiasesinclinicaldiagnosishowaiactsasanexternalcalibratorinmanagedchaoseduar-260608115108-df509cb6-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"📋 ABOUT THIS PRESENTATION\nThis presentation explores the cognitive mechanisms behind diagnostic errors in clinical practice and presents a framework for how artificial intelligence can serve as an \"external calibrator\" of clinical reasoning — not as a replacement for physicians, but as a tool to mitigate systematic cognitive biases.\n\n🎯 CORE THEMES\n• Why 60-80% of diagnostic errors stem from cognitive biases, not knowledge gaps\n• Dual Process Theory: System 1 (fast/intuitive) vs System 2 (slow/analytical) in clinical decision-making\n• Key cognitive biases: Anchoring, Premature Closure, Availability Heuristic, Confirmation Bias\n• The \"Noise\" problem: why equally qualified physicians give different diagnoses\n• Cynefin Framework: medicine as a complex adaptive system (\"managed chaos\")\n• AI as a Bayesian calibrator: updating probabilities and challenging initial hypotheses\n• Human-in-the-loop model: the \"Centaur Doctor\" of the future\n• Practical tools: checklists, structured pauses, mandatory alternative hypotheses\n\n📊 TARGET AUDIENCE\n• Clinicians and medical professionals\n• Healthcare AI developers and researchers\n• Medical educators and students\n• Health technology policymakers\n• Clinical decision-making researchers\n\n💡 KEY INSIGHTS\n1. Diagnostic errors are a built-in feature of human cognition, not a bug\n2. Experience accelerates decisions but increases reliance on automatic patterns\n3. AI's greatest value lies in non-coincidence — when it disagrees with the physician\n4. The future physician is an \"operator of complex systems,\" not just a knowledge carrier\n5. A good physician builds processes where errors become difficult to make\n\n👤 ABOUT THE AUTHOR\nEduard Koshilko is an independent researcher specializing in cognitive aspects of medical decision-making and the role of AI as an external calibrator of clinical hypotheses. His analytical work focuses on the intersection of probabilistic thinking, cognitive biases in diagnostics, and the integration of AI into clinical workflows.\nHis research examines how physicians make decisions under uncertainty and how structured approaches — including AI tools — can compensate for the limitations of human perception and reasoning.\n\n🔗 CONTACT \u0026 RESOURCES\n• LinkedIn: https://www.linkedin.com/in/koshilko\n• ORCID: https://orcid.org/0009-0000-9874-6721\n• Academia.edu: Eduard Koshilko\n\n⚠️ LEGAL DISCLAIMER / RECHTLICHER HINWEIS / \n[EN] This presentation is for analytical and educational purposes only. It does not constitute medical advice, diagnosis, or treatment guidance. The author does not engage in clinical practice. For health-related matters, consult qualified healthcare professionals.\n[DE] Diese Präsentation dient ausschließlich analytischen und Bildungszwecken. Sie stellt keine medizinische Beratung, Diagnose oder Behandlungsanleitung dar. Der Autor übt keine klinische Praxis aus. Bei Gesundheitsfragen wenden Sie sich bitte an qualifiziertes medizinisches Fachpersonal.","tags":["cognitive biases","clinical diagnosis","medical decision-making"],"url":"https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/cognitive-biases-in-clinical-diagnosis-how-ai-acts-as-an-external-calibrator-in-managed-chaos-eduar-pptx/287958396","userLogin":"ssuser7b7117","userName":"Eduard Koshilko","viewCount":36},{"algorithmId":"4","displayTitle":"Multiple Sclerosis. Causes, Diagnosis, Management, Physiotherapy. Neurologica...","extension":"pdf","isSavedByCurrentUser":false,"pageCount":48,"score":0,"slideshowId":"287998264","sourceName":"LATEST","strippedTitle":"multiple-sclerosis-causes-diagnosis-management-physiotherapy-neurological-physiotherapy","type":"presentation","thumbnail":"https://cdn.slidesharecdn.com/ss_thumbnails/ms-260610165031-91c9809a-thumbnail.jpg?width=640\u0026height=640\u0026fit=bounds","description":"Detailed insights into Multiple Sclerosis including etiology, symptoms, diagnosis, disease course, and physical therapy interventions for mobility, pain, fatigue, spasticity, and coordina